tford VT."},{"war":"American Revolutionary War","war_id":"WAR004","rank":"Private","rank_start":"Private","rank_end":"Private","rank_year_start":1780,"rank_year_end":1780,"unit":"Capt. Joshua Hazen's Hartford Co., Vermont Militia","notes":"Royalton Alarm, October 1780 (Vermont militia response to the Tory-and-Indian raid on Royalton VT). NSSAR membership #117807. Documented in John E. Goodrich, Rolls of Soldiers in the Revolutionary War, 1904, pp. 283-284. This Vermont militia service post-dates his Connecticut Line service (1775-1777) and reflects his 1777 migration to Hartford VT."}],"bio":{"display_name":"David Newton","first_name":"David","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"residence":{"city":"Hartford","county":"Windsor","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"migration","header":"Crossed to Vermont on the frozen Connecticut River","body":"David Newton moved his family from Connecticut to Hartford Vermont in 1777, traveling in the dead of winter and using the ice-covered Connecticut River as a highway according to family tradition. Just before his marriage four years earlier he had bought twenty-five acres of the Hazen home lot in Woodbury Connecticut."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Family record called most remarkable in the country","body":"A Newton family historian called this household's record 'the most remarkable one known in the United States, if not in the world, in respect to the number of children, their individual length of life, and the aggregate of the ages of the whole family.' David and Mary raised at least nine documented children in Hartford Vermont; David lived to eighty-six."}],"slug":"david-newton-1753"},"I00101":{"id":"I00101","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_fr