riage","header":"Married by Connecticut's future governor in 1680","body":"His marriage to Lydia Ford on April 14, 1680 in Milford was performed by Major Robert Treat, then Deputy Governor of Connecticut. Treat would become Governor in 1683 and remain in office until 1698 — the same year John Newton died."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Built his house next to his father's","body":"He built his house immediately adjacent to Roger Newton Sr.'s on the same Milford home lot. His daughter Prudence — eighteen months old — was 'just old enough to run across the yard to her grandfather's' during Roger's final illness in early 1683."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"May 1699 deposition: widow Lydia and four children","body":"He died in May 1699 in Milford. Lydia's deposition for the May 18 estate inventory survives, listing their children — Prudence about 18, Thomas about 17, Ezekiel, and John about 2. She was 38 and a widow with four to raise."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Lydia Ford lived 48 years a widow","body":"Lydia Ford remained a widow until her death in 1747 at age 86 — 48 years after John's death. Milford Land Records show numerous transactions in her name, and her 1746 will divided the estate among her surviving children and grandchildren."}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"artworks":[],"bio":{"display_name":"John Newton","first_name":"John","last_name":"Newton","married_names":[]},"documents":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"john-newton-1656"},"I00012":{"id":"I00012","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1661,"month":3,"day":15,"city":"Milford","county":"New Haven County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1747,"month